<div id="idg_container-2">
<div id="idg_slot-1">
<h1>What is indigo?</h1>

<p>
Indigo provides the basic structure of a site and a collection of modules 
which retrieve and format content, respectively.
</p>

<p>
It can sit on top of basically whatever you want, be it
plain text files, <a href="https://www.sqlite.org/"><img src="views/blocks/elements/link_ext.png" width="11" height="10" alt="">sqlite</a> database 
files, or for example, it would not be hard to program it to display blog 
postings that you manage using <a href="https://wordpress.org"><img src="views/blocks/elements/link_ext.png" width="11" height="10" alt="">WordPress</a>.
</p>
<p>
To date, indigo can only generate HTML/CSS but it could be extended to
support other markup languages as well.
</p>

<h2>Indigo is not a <abbr title="Content Management System">CMS</abbr></h2>

<p>
Indigo does not provide a mechanism for organizing, editing or
storing your work product. You can have an arbitrary number of different 
site maps and modules side-by-side; you can also give your site as many 
designs to choose from as you wish. On the other hand, while it makes it 
easy to structure your content, e.g. in accordance with a 
specific file system layout, it provides no mechanism for that.
</p>

<p>Then again, if you want an editor for the site's outline, template
pages, or similar things, it should provide a good starting point for
you to get your programmer's hands dirty.</p>

<h2>Indigo works well with standards</h2>

<p>
The pages indigo generates are comprised of HTML and CSS, 
combined into a single document.
You can still style your content as usual - without running into namespace 
problems - while the code snippets you have clamped in happily churn out 
dynamically generated markup as well as layout information. 
This also helps to avoid issues with
aggressively caching browsers; or those that don't like style sheets
the name of which ends in .php - regardless of the MIME type provided.
</p>

<p>
With a few exceptions - mainly the mobile version - the 
layouts in the documentation do not use JavaScript. Instead, expecially
for the navigation, they rely heavily on the creative use of CSS 
as described for instance on
<a href="https://alistapart.com/blog/topic/css/"><img src="views/blocks/elements/link_ext.png" width="11" height="10" alt="">a list apart</a>.
</p>

<div style="background: url(views/blocks/elements/bg_div.png); width: 100%; height: 100%; border: solid black; border-width: 1px;"><blockquote style="margin-left: 1em;">
    For more magic have a look at the <a href="http://csszengarden.com"><img src="views/blocks/elements/link_ext.png" width="11" height="10" alt="">CSS Zen Garden</a>:<br>
    &ldquo;A demonstration of what can be accomplished through CSS-based design.&rdquo;
</blockquote><img src="views/blocks/elements/lightbulb.png" alt="" style="float: right; position: relative; bottom: 40px; right: 2px;"></div>

<p>
In fact, the above paragraph is a simple
<code>&lt;blockquote&gt;</code>. Some designs need it surrounded by
extra markup; they can add that themselves using a filter.
</p>

<h2>Indigo is flexible</h2>

<p>
	While it is fair to say that indigo mainly serves to style
	web sites that follow conventional patterns as well as provide
	methods to use common sources of dynamic content, this is far from
	the end of what you can do with it.
</p>

<p>
	Since the xml files that it reads only serve to populate
	a tree of objects (or rather, a forest) with instances, that
	then do their respective jobs when the tree is finally walked,
	every aspect of	it is accessible programmatically. For an example, 
	look at the <code>index.php</code> file and how it conjures up
	an error page when the requested document does not exist.
</p>

<p>
	But even the folder structure is created in the same way, so
	finally one could go as far as create a whole site that
	is completely virtual, rule driven, and potentially interfacing
	with several pre-existing content providers.
</p>

<p>
	Even if this seems a little far-fetched, please bear in mind
	that things that appear in the same places on a page still do not
	necessarily need to come from the same source, therefore making it 
	easy to experiment with intelligent caching mechanisms, failover,
	etc.
</p>

<h2>Indigo is easy to extend</h2>

<p>
	In fact, it grows all the time - instead of writing 
	task-specific code, these days I mostly create the needed features 
	directly in the upstream version.
	More often than not, however, I end up throwing out redundancies 
	instead	of adding something really new to the core library.
</p>

<div style="background: url(views/blocks/elements/bg_div.png); width: 100%; height: 100%; border: solid black; border-width: 1px;"><blockquote style="margin-left: 1em;">
   For an in-depth discussion of the concepts that in part inspired indigo have a look at 
        <a href="https://mitp-content-server.mit.edu/books/content/sectbyfn/books_pres_0/6515/sicp.zip/full-text/book/book-Z-H-19.html"><img src="views/blocks/elements/link_ext.png" width="11" height="10" alt="">The Wizard Book</a>, especially the section on streams.
</blockquote><img src="views/blocks/elements/lightbulb.png" alt="" style="float: right; position: relative; bottom: 40px; right: 2px;"></div>

<p>
	Once you get the hang of the three-dimensional structure 
	(polymorphism is present both in the php class hierarchy 
	and the trees that indigo itself implements) you
	will find that there is almost always an obvious place
	where to add new functionality. And don't worry about breaking
	existing code: it only operates on streams after all.
</p>


</div>
</div>
